revision.text:
An '''International University Games''' ({{lang-de|Studenten-Weltspiele}}<ref name="poster"/>) was an international [[multi-sport event]] held between 20–27 August 1939 in [[Vienna]], [[German Reich]] (now Vienna, [[Austria]]),<ref name="poster"/><ref name="Rebhann1995">{{cite book|last=Rebhann|first=Fritz Maria|title=Die braunen Jahre: Wien 1938-1945|year=1995|publisher=Wiener Journal Zeitschriftenverl.|isbn=9783853080139|page=78}}</ref> which had originally been scheduled as the official 1939 staging of the Summer [[International University Games]] awarded to Vienna by the [[Confederation Internationale des Etudiants]] (CIE) in January 1938, prior to Austria's absorption into [[Nazi Germany]] by the [[Anschluss]].<ref name="GlasgowHerald">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sjg1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=R6YLAAAAIBAJ&pg=4545%2C143265|title=World Student Games: Surprise Change of Venue|date=1 June 1939|work=The Glasgow Herald|page=17|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Students in Search of Their University: An International "conversation" Between Students on "Education in the Modern University", Luxemburg, May 22-25, 1938|year=1939|publisher=International Institute of Intellectual Cooperation|page=162}}</ref> The [[National Socialist German Students' League]] (NSDStB) withdrew from the CIE in May 1939,<ref name="GlasgowHerald" /> and the CIE at short notice moved it's version of the [[1939 International University Games]] to [[Monte Carlo]].
The formal opening was by [[Bernhard Rust]], the [[Reich Ministry of Science, Education and Culture|Reich Minister of Science, Education and Culture]], on 20 August in the [[Prater Stadium]], the main venue of the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beeldbankwo2.nl/detail.jsp?action=detail&recordidx=1|title=Feierliche Eröffnung der Studentenweltspiele 1939|publisher=Beeldbank WO2 [Image Bank WW2]|language=German|accessdate=22 May 2016|location=Amsterdam|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130912131044/http://www.beeldbankwo2.nl/detail.jsp?action=detail&recordidx=1|archive-date=2013-09-12|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wien.gv.at/freizeit/sportamt/annodazumal/sportstaetten/stadion.html|title=Das Wiener Stadion (Ernst-Happel-Stadion)|work=Wien.gv.at|publisher=Vienna City Council|language=German|accessdate=22 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807112739/https://www.wien.gv.at/freizeit/sportamt/annodazumal/sportstaetten/stadion.html#|archive-date=2016-08-07|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> The NSDStB invited many nations to the Vienna games, but most entrants were nations affiliated with the [[Axis powers]].<ref name="GlasgowHerald" /><ref name="KotekBlumenau2015">{{cite book|last1=Kotek|first1=Joel|last2=Blumenau|first2=trans Ralph|title=Students and the Cold War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=weqwCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA242|accessdate=19 May 2016|date=30 December 2015|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=9781349248384|pages=242, note 3.}}</ref> The following countries were reported to have participated in the games: [[Kingdom of Bulgaria]], [[Estonia]], [[Finland]], [[German Reich]], [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920–46)|Kingdom of Hungary]], [[Kingdom of Italy]], [[Empire of Japan]], [[Peru]], [[Slovak Republic (1939–45)|Slovak Republic]], [[Spanish State]], [[Union of South Africa]], [[Sweden]], and [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Ernst Söllinger, Ein Münchener in Darmstadt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCTTl27097cC&pg=PA89|publisher=Raimund Kluber|language=German|page=89}}</ref>{{dead link|date=July 2018}} The [[International Institute of Intellectual Cooperation]] stated in 1940, "The results of the Monaco Games were much superior to those of the Vienna Games."<ref>{{cite journal|year=1940|journal=Intellectual Co-operation Bulletin|publisher=International Institute of Intellectual Co-operation|page=134|title=?}}</ref>
